eet by modifying two existing buses, becoming the first agency in the nation to do so.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wald |first=Matthew L. |date=April 7, 1989 |title=Alternative-Fuel Vehicles Move From Fancy to Fact |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/04/07/business/alternative-fuel-vehicles-move-from-fancy-to-fact.html?pagewanted=all |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=September 11, 2016}}</ref> As of 2018, 118 of the 153 buses in the agency's fleet run on compressed natural gas. Other models are diesel\u2013electric hybrids or use electric batteries.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cohen |first=Josh |date=October 11, 2018 |title=How an explosion in Canada threatened to stop buses in Pierce County |url=https://crosscut.com/2018/10/how-explosion-canada-threatened-stop-buses-pierce-county |work=[[Crosscut.com]] |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Bus===\n{{See also|Sound Transit#Fleet}}\n:''{{As of|2016|07|df=US}}''<ref name=\"TDP\">{{cite report |title=Draft Transit Development Plan, 2016\u20132021 |chapter=Appendix D \u2013 Inventories |pages=D1\u2013D39 |url=http://www.piercetransit.org/file_viewer.php?id=2833 |publisher=Pierce Transit |accessdate=September 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Manufacturer\n!Model\n!Year\n!Fleet<br />Numbers\n!{{tooltip|Qty.|Quantity}}\n!Length\n!Fuel Type\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Image\n|-\n|rowspan=7|[[Gillig Corporation|Gillig]]\n|[[Gillig Phantom|Phantom 40']]\n|1999\n|align=right|{{sort|8018|8018\u20138069}}\n|align=right|23\n|align=right rowspan=7|{{convert|40|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|[[Diesel engine|Diesel]]\n|\n*Reserve fleet\n*Acquired from [[Sound Transit]]\n*8022, 8026\u20138027, 8030, 8036\u20138042, 8046\u20138054, 8058, 8060\u20138062, 8064\u20138065, 8067 retired\n*Some buses used on [[Sound Transit Express]]\n|[[File:Pierce Transit 8055 at Union Station.jpg|150px]]\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Gillig Low Floor|Low Floor]] CNG (G27D102N4)\n|2015\n|align=right|{{sort|0251|251\u2013260}}\n|align=