5 || ''in service'' || 14 || 7000-7013\n|}\n\n===Ferry===\n* [[Steilacoom-Anderson Island Ferry]]\n\n==Adjoining transit agencies==\n*[[King County Metro]]\n*[[Kitsap Transit]]\n*[[Intercity Transit]]\n*[[Washington State Ferries]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official Website|http://www.piercetransit.org}}\n{{clear}}\n{{Puget Sound Transit}}\n\n[[Category:Bus transportation in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Paratransit services in the United States]]\n[[Category:Transit authorities with natural gas buses]]\n[[Category:Sound Transit]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Pierce County, Washington]]\n[[Category:1979 establishments in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Transit agencies in Washington (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Local public transit operator in Pierce County, Washington, including the city of Tacoma}}\n{{Infobox Bus transit\n| name            = Pierce Transit\n| logo            = Pierce Transit logo.svg\n| logo_size       = \n| image           = Pierce Transit C40LF.jpg\n| image_size      = 250\n| image_caption   = A [[compressed natural gas]] bus operated by Pierce Transit\n| company_slogan  = \n| founded         = 1979\n| headquarters    = 3701 96th Street Southwest<br />[[Lakewood, Washington]]\n| locale          = [[Pierce County, Washington]]\n| service_area    = \n| service_type    = [[Transit bus|Bus]], [[vanpool]], [[paratransit]]\n| alliance        = \n| routes          = \n| hubs            = \n| fleet           = 155 buses\n| ridership       = \n| fuel_type       = Diesel, [[compressed natural gas]]\n| operator        = \n| ceo             = Sue Dreier\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.piercetransit.org/}}\n|annual_ridership=9,104,337 (2015)}}\n\n'''Pierce Transit''', officially the '''Pierce County Public Transportation Benefit Area Corporation''', is an operator of [[public transit]] in [[Pierce County, Washington|Pierce County]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]. It operates a variety of services, including fixed-route [[bus]]es, [[dial-a-ride|dial-a-ride transportation]], [[vanpool]] and ride-matching for [[carpool]]s. The agency's service area covers the urbanized portions of Pierce County, part of the [[Seattle metropolitan area]], and includes the city of [[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]].\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Streetcars in Tacoma, Washington}}\n\nPublic transportation in Pierce County historically focused on the city of Tacoma, which laid its first [[streetcar]] lines in 1888. The streetcars were phased out in the 1930s and replaced with citywide bus service, with the last line closing in 1938.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Malloy |first1=Dick |last2=Ott |first2=John S. |year=1993 |title=The Tacoma Public Utility Story: The First 100 Years, 1893\u20131993 |publisher=Tacoma Public Utilities |oclc=29528435}}</ref> The operators of the streetcar and bus systems, Tacoma Transit Company, was acquired by the city government in 1961 for $750,000. Under city ownership, the system was funded by a $0.75 monthly household tax first levied in 1965.<ref name=\"1984Report\">{{cite report |author=Public Transportation Office |date=October 1984 |title=Public Transportation in Washington State |url=http://ntl.bts.gov/lib/12000/12700/12792/12792.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=Washington State Department of Transportation |via=[[National Transportation Library]] |chapter=Local Transit |pages=105\u2013106 |oclc=13007541 |accessdate=September 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nA [[public transportation benefit area]] (PTBA) was created in 1979 with the goal of establishing a countywide bus system. On November 6, 1979, voters in Tacoma approved a 0.3 percent [[sales tax]] to fund a new transit system, the Pierce County Transportation Benefit Area or \"Pierce Transit\". Pierce Transit took over Tacoma Transit's routes on January 1, 1980, and over the following year annexed other systems throughout the county.<ref name=\"1984Report\"/>\n\nPierce Transit began operating [[express bus service]] from Lakewood and Tacoma to [[Downtown Seattle]] on September 17, 1990.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shatzkin |first=Kate |date=September 17, 1990 |title=Commuters happy to let others do driving: Tacoma-to-Seattle bus has a successful start |page=D1 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19900917&slug=1093697 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 11, 2016}}</ref> The routes were later converted into [[Sound Transit Express]] routes, funded by the [[Sound Transit|regional transit authority]] and operated by Pierce Transit, in 1999.<ref>{{cite news |last=Whitely |first=Peyton |date=September 17, 1999 |title=Buses ready to roll |page=B1 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19990917&slug=2983670 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 11, 2016}}</ref> The agency opened its central bus hub at [[Tacoma Dome Station]] in 1997, where [[Sounder commuter rail]] and [[Tacoma Link]] [[light rail]] service began operating in 2000 and 2003, respectively.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kaiman |first=Beth |date=September 12, 2000 |title=Commuter rail service to begin; New trains will run between Tacoma and Seattle |page=B1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lindblom |first=Mike |date=August 23, 2003 |title=Sound Transit starts small with Tacoma Link system |page=B1 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030823&slug=link23m |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe passage of [[Initiative 695]] in 1999 eliminated the use of [[motor vehicle excise tax]], a funding source for local transit throughout the state, leading to service cuts at Pierce Transit despite it later being ruled unconstitutional by the [[Washington Supreme Court]]. In 2000, 14 percent of service was reduced and a fare increase was set to temporarily make up for revenue from the tax, which made up 38 percent of the agency's operating budget. Voters approved a 0.3 percent sales tax increase to fund transit service during a special election in February 2002,<ref>{{cite news |last=Corvin |first=Aaron |date=February 6, 2002 |title=Pierce County voters approve sales-tax increase for transit agency |page=1 |work=The News Tribune}}</ref> preventing a planned cut in bus service of up to 45 percent, and up to 25 percent for paratransit.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 5, 2001 |title=Pierce Transit approves request for sales tax request on 2002 ballot |url=http://www.tacomadailyindex.com/blog/pierce-transit-approves-request-for-sales-tax-request-on-2002-ballot/64701/ |work=[[Tacoma Daily Index]] |accessdate=September 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Corvin |first=Aaron |date=January 28, 2002 |title=Future of Tacoma bus system riding on levy |page=1 |work=The News Tribune}}</ref>\n\n===Funding crisis===\nIn 2012, Pierce Transit argued that it was in an unsustainable state due to its reserves running out, and as a result, must cut service by 53% in order to become sustainable again. Pierce Transit argued that if taxes within its service area were increased by 0.3%, Pierce Transit would not have had to cut service, and instead could have improved service by 23%.<ref>http://www.piercetransit.org/prop1/</ref> Opponents of the 0.3% tax increase in Pierce County (also known as Proposition 1) advertised a sales tax increase to 10.1% (the \"highest on the West Coast\"), but in reality that rate would have only applied to motor vehicles due to the state motor vehicle sales and use tax.<ref>http://dor.wa.gov/content/FindTaxesAndRates/OtherTaxes/tax_motorvehicle.aspx</ref> Most taxable goods and services would have been taxed at the rate of 9.8%. \nPierce Transit proposed a similar increase in sales tax in 2011, which was eventually rejected by the public.<ref>http://www.thenewstribune.com/2011/01/23/1513538/crisis-point-for-pierce-transit.html</ref>   Proposition 1, proposed in the 2012 general election, has also been rejected by the public.<ref>http://blogs.seattleweekly.com/dailyweekly/2012/11/pierce_transit_prop_1_fails_defated_bus_cuts_pierce_county_transportation_tacoma.php</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, the cities of Bonney Lake, Buckley, DuPont, Orting, and Sumner withdrew from the boundaries of Pierce Transit's service area, which shrunk to {{convert|292|sqmi|sqkm}}.<ref name=\"PTBA-2012\">{{cite web |date=June 2012 |title=Summer 2012 Report to the Community |publisher=Pierce Transit |url=http://www.piercetransit.org/pdfs/report-to-community/2012RTC_Final_June27.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120915045828/http://piercetransit.org/pdfs/report-to-community/2012RTC_Final_June27.pdf |archivedate=September 15, 2012 |accessdate=April 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Bus rapid transit service===\n\nPierce Transit plans to build a [[bus rapid transit]] system on Pacific Avenue between Tacoma and [[Spanaway, Washington|Spanaway]], replacing a {{convert|14.4|mi|km|adj=mid}} section of Route 1. The $150 million project, partially funded by [[Sound Transit 3]] and the federal government, is scheduled to begin construction in 2020 and open in 2022.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ruud |first=Candice |date=April 6, 2018 |title=Wave as they pass your car. Fast buses could be coming to a long stretch of Pacific Avenue |url=http://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/article208076634.html |work=The News Tribune |accessdate=April 6, 2018}}</ref> The bus rapid transit line is planned to use curb-side and median stations, with {{convert|3.6|mi|km}} of dedicated bus lanes and 32 total stations.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sailor |first=Craig |date=April 10, 2019 |title=Pierce Transit board chooses middle-of-the-road solution for $150 million bus project |url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/article229033419.html |work=The News Tribune |accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Administration==\n\nPierce Transit is operated by nine-member Board of Commissioners composed of elected officials throughout the county. The Board of Commissioners operates under a Chief Executive Officer, Sue Drier.<ref name=commis>[http://www.piercetransit.org/commis.htm Pierce County Public Transportation Benefit Area Corporation]</ref> A staff of approximately 1,000 man the five departments, with over 50% working in Transit Operations.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\n===Police===\nPierce Transit contracts with the Pierce County Sheriff's Department for police services. There are currently 16 patrol deputies assigned full-time to Pierce Transit. The command staff of Pierce Transit Police include two Supervising Sergeants and the Transit Police Chief(provided by the Pierce County Sheriff's Department - under contract). The Pierce Transit system is also patrolled by 17 specially commissioned Peace Officers (Public Safety Officers).{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\n==Services==\nAs of 2012, Pierce Transit served a {{convert|292|sqmi|km2|sing=on}} area with a population of approximately 557,000.<ref name=\"PTBA-2012\"/> Areas served include [[Auburn, Washington|Auburn]], [[Edgewood, Washington|Edgewood]], [[Federal Way, Washington|Federal Way]], [[Fife, Washington|Fife]], [[Fircrest, Washington|Fircrest]], [[Gig Harbor, Washington|Gig Harbor]], [[Joint Base Lewis\u2013McChord]], [[Lakewood, Washington|Lakewood]], [[Milton, Washington|Milton]], [[Pacific, Washington|Pacific]], [[Purdy, Washington|Purdy]], [[Puyallup, Washington|Puyallup]], [[Ruston, Washington|Ruston]], [[South Hill, Washington|South Hill]], [[Steilacoom, Washington|Steilacoom]], [[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]] and [[University Place, Washington|University Place]].\n\nIn 2008, 19 million people utilized its services. 272 [[wheelchair]]-accessible [[bus]]es circulate between 3,300 bus stops, 626 bus shelters and 28 park-and-ride lots. Additionally, Pierce Transit runs 11 transit centers and stations. Pierce Transit also provides vanpool, ridematching and express transportation between counties. Disabled passengers who are not able to use Pierce Transit's buses have access to a special transportation system called SHUTTLE.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\n=== Bus routes ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Route  #\n!Route Name\n!Notes\n!Continues as\n|-\n|1\n|6th Ave\u2013Pacific Ave\n|\n|\n|-\n|2\n|S 19th St\u2013Bridgeport Way\n|\n|\n|-\n|3\n|Lakewood\u2013Tacoma\n|\n|\n|-\n|4\n|Lakewood\u2013South Hill\n|\n|\n|-\n|10\n|Pearl St\n|\n|\n|-\n|11\n|Point Defiance\n|\n|41\n|-\n|13\n|N 30th St\n|Monday\u2013Friday only\n|\n|-\n|16\n|North End\n|\n|48\n|-\n|28\n|S 12th St\n|\n|\n|-\n|41\n|S 56th St\u2013Salishan\n|\n|11\n|-\n|42\n|McKinley Ave\n|\n|\n|-\n|45\n|Yakima\n|\n|\n|-\n|48\n|Sheridan\u2013M St\n|\n|16\n|-\n|52\n|Fircrest\u2013TCC\n|\n|\n|-\n|53\n|University Place\n|\n|55\n|-\n|54\n|38th St\u2013Portland Ave\n|\n|\n|-\n|55\n|Tacoma Mall\n|\n|53\n|-\n|57\n|Union\u2013S 19th St\u2013Hilltop\n|\n|\n|-\n|63\n|NE Tacoma Express\n|Weekday, peak-hours only\n|\n|-\n|100\n|Gig Harbor\n|\n|\n|-\n|102\n|Gig Harbor Express\n|Weekday, peak-hours only\n|\n|-\n|202\n|72nd St\n|\n|409\n|-\n|206\n|Pacific Hwy\u2013Tillicum\n|\n|\n|-\n|212\n|Steilacoom\n|\n|214\n|-\n|214\n|Washington\n|\n|212\n|-\n|400\n|Puyallup\u2013Downtown Tacoma\n|Monday\u2013Friday only\n|\n|-\n|402\n|Meridian\n|\n|\n|-\n|409\n|Puyallup\u201372nd St TC\n|\n|202\n|-\n|425\n|Puyallup Connector\n|Monday\u2013Saturday only\n|\n|-\n|497\n|Lakeland Hills Express\n|Weekday, peak-hours only\n|\n|-\n|500\n|Federal Way\n|\n|\n|-\n|501\n|Milton\u2013Federal Way\n|\n|\n|}\n\n===Fares===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Service !! Adult !! Youth/Senior/Disabled\n|-\n| Local || $2 || $1\n|-\n| Pierce Transit Local 24-Hour Pass || $5 || $2.50\n|-\n| Pierce Transit Local Monthly Pass || $72 || $36 \n|-\n| Summer Youth Pass || - || $36 (Youth only)\n|}\n*Under 6 ride free with a fare-paying rider; limit is 3.\n*Passengers aged 6 to 18 pay youth fare.\n*Summer Youth Pass only valid on Pierce Transit from June to August.\n*Passengers 19 to 64 pay adult fare unless they have a valid regional reduced fare permit.\n\nFares last updated on: 3/1/2016 <ref>http://www.piercetransit.org/PT-fares</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n\n===Transit Centers===\n{{colbegin}}\n*512 Park and Ride\n*72nd St Transit Center\n*10th and Commerce (Downtown Tacoma)\n*Lakewood Transit Center\n*Lakewood Sounder Station\n*Parkland Transit Center\n*South Hill Mall Transit Center\n*Tacoma Dome Station\n*Tacoma Mall Transit Center\n*TCC Transit Center\n{{colend}}\n\n==Fleet==\n\nIn 1986, Pierce Transit began experimenting with [[compressed natural gas]] as a fuel source for its bus fleet by modifying two existing buses, becoming the first agency in the nation to do so.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wald |first=Matthew L. |date=April 7, 1989 |title=Alternative-Fuel Vehicles Move From Fancy to Fact |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/04/07/business/alternative-fuel-vehicles-move-from-fancy-to-fact.html?pagewanted=all |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=September 11, 2016}}</ref> As of 2018, 118 of the 153 buses in the agency's fleet run on compressed natural gas. Other models are diesel\u2013electric hybrids or use electric batteries.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cohen |first=Josh |date=October 11, 2018 |title=How an explosion in Canada threatened to stop buses in Pierce County |url=https://crosscut.com/2018/10/how-explosion-canada-threatened-stop-buses-pierce-county |work=[[Crosscut.com]] |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Bus===\n{{See also|Sound Transit#Fleet}}\n:''{{As of|2016|07|df=US}}''<ref name=\"TDP\">{{cite report |title=Draft Transit Development Plan, 2016\u20132021 |chapter=Appendix D \u2013 Inventories |pages=D1\u2013D39 |url=http://www.piercetransit.org/file_viewer.php?id=2833 |publisher=Pierce Transit |accessdate=September 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Manufacturer\n!Model\n!Year\n!Fleet<br />Numbers\n!{{tooltip|Qty.|Quantity}}\n!Length\n!Fuel Type\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Image\n|-\n|rowspan=7|[[Gillig Corporation|Gillig]