svg\n| logo_size       = 120px\n| image           =\n| image_size      = 350px\n| image_caption   = \n| company_slogan  = \n| parent          = City of Detroit\n| founded         = 1922\n| headquarters    = 1301 East Warren Avenue\n| locale          = \n| service_area    = Detroit, limited suburban service\n| service_type    = [[Bus service|Bus]], [[express bus]], [[paratransit]]\n| alliance        = \n| routes          = 43 \n| stops           = \n| hubs            = [[Rosa Parks Transit Center]]<br /> State Fairgrounds Transit Center\n| stations        = \n| lounge          = \n| fleet           = 300 buses<ref>{{cite news|last=Burns|first=Gus|title=Detroit Mayor Mike Duggan announces firing of DDOT director in speech; bus boss says it's news to him|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/detroit/index.ssf/2014/01/mayor_duggan_fires_ddot_direct.html|accessdate=26 October 2011|newspaper=MLive.com|date=7 January 2014}}</ref> \n| ridership       = 91,700 (Q4 2015)<ref>{{cite web|title=Fourth Quarter, 2015|url=http://www.apta.com/resources/statistics/Documents/Ridership/2015-q4-ridership-APTA.pdf|work=Public Transportation Ridership Report|publisher=American Public Transportation Association|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> \n| fuel_type       = Diesel\n| operator        = City of Detroit\n| leader_type     = Director\n| leader          = Angelica Jones\n| website         = [http://www.detroitmi.gov/ddot Detroit Department of Transportation]\n}}\nThe '''Detroit Department of Transportation''' ('''DDOT''', pronounced {{respell|DEE|dot}}) is the [[public transportation]] operator of [[transit bus|city bus service]] in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]].  In existence since 1922, it has headquarters in the [[Midtown Detroit|Midtown]] section of Detroit and is a municipal department of the city government. DDOT partners with the [[Suburban Mobility Authority for Regional Transportation]] (SMART).\n\n==Services==\nAs the largest public transit agency in the state of [[Michigan]], DDOT primarily serves the city of Detroit, with some additional and limited service to nearby cities of [[Dearborn, Michigan|Dearborn]], [[Hamtramck, Michigan|Hamtramck]], [[Highland Park, Michigan|Highland Park]] (both are Detroit enclaves), [[Harper Woods, Michigan|Harper Woods]], [[Livonia, Michigan|Livonia]], [[Redford Township, Michigan|Redford Township]], [[River Rouge, Michigan|River Rouge]] and [[Southfield, Michigan|Southfield]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ci.detroit.mi.us/Portals/0/docs/deptoftransportation/pdfs/DDOT_System_Map_2009.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308162144/http://www.ci.detroit.mi.us/Portals/0/docs/deptoftransportation/pdfs/DDOT_System_Map_2009.pdf |archivedate=2012-03-08 }}</ref>  DDOT has a fare and ride agreement with the [[Suburban Mobility Authority for Regional Transportation]] as it supplements the city with bus service linking the city to the rest of [[Metro Detroit]] and [[Detroit Metropolitan Wayne County Airport]].  Bus service generally operates between 5 a.m. and 12:30&nbsp;a.m. Monday through Saturday, while Sunday service starts approximately 7 a.m. and ends between 8 and 9 p.m.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.detroitmi.gov/Departments/DetroitDepartmentofTransportation/BusInformation/PocketSchedules/tabid/1255/Default.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-04-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110916070914/http://www.detroitmi.gov/Departments/DetroitDepartmentofTransportation/BusInformation/PocketSchedules/tabid/1255/Default.aspx |archive-date=2011-09-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Routes 1\u201310 and 16 have [[24/7 service]].<ref name=changes>{{cite web|title=New DDOT ConnectTen service to add 500 trips per week with 15-minute peak hour frequency, Wi-Fi|url=https://detroitmi.gov/news/new-ddot-connectten-service-add-500-trips-week-15-minute-peak-hour-frequency-wi-fi|website=Detroit Department of Transportation|date=August 28, 2018|accessdate=November 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlong with operating fixed-route bus service, DDOT also operates MetroLift, an on-demand paratransit service with 220 to 240 wheelchair accessible vehicles. DDOT contracts with three providers for this service: Checker Cab, Enjoi Transportation, and Lakeside Divisions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Detroit MetroLift\u2019s Disabled Riders Enjoy Benefits of New, Expanded Service|url=http://www.detroitmi.gov/Portals/0/Docs/Bus%20Schedules/MetroLift_MI_Expanded_Service.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317192730/http://www.detroitmi.gov/Portals/0/Docs/Bus%20Schedules/MetroLift_MI_Expanded_Service.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 March 2015|website=www.detroitmi.gov/|publisher=Detroit Department of Transportation|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe DDOT began its life as the Department of Street Railways (DSR) in 1922 after the acquisition of the privately owned [[Detroit United Railway]] (DUR), which had controlled much of Detroit's mass transit operations since its incorporation in 1901.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://apps.detnews.com/apps/history/index.php?id=50 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130215205909/http://apps.detnews.com/apps/history/index.php?id=50 |archivedate=2013-02-15 }}</ref>  The DSR added bus service when it created the Motorbus Division in 1925.  At the height of its operation in 1941, the DSR operated 20 [[streetcar]] lines with 910 streetcars.<ref name=detroittransithistory>{{cite web|title=DEPARTMENT OF STREET RAILWAYS (D.S.R.) 1941 STREETCAR ROUTE MAP|url=http://www.detroittransithistory.info/DSR/RailMap-1941.html|work=detroittransithistory.info|accessdate=2014-03-23}}</ref> By 1952, only four streetcar lines remained: Woodward, Gratiot, Michigan and Jefferson. Streetcar services was discontinued in April 1956 with the decommissioning of the Woodward line. The DSR formally became the DDOT in 1974 under the Detroit City Charter.<ref name=\"TransitHistory\">{{cite web|title=Detroit Transit History.info|url=http://www.detroittransithistory.info/|work=detroittransithistory.info|accessdate=2014-03-23}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2009 and 2012, the system's seven remaining limited and [[express bus]] routes (70, 71, 72, 73, 74, 76, and 78) were discontinued.<ref>{{cite web|title=DDOT Routes & Numbers|url=http://www.detroittransithistory.info/DDOT/DDOTRouteNumbers.html|publisher=Detroit Transit History.info|accessdate=7 January 2014}}</ref> Starting January 1, 2012, management of DDOT was contracted out to [[Parsons Brinckerhoff]], an engineering and management firm. The firm subsequently subcontracted the management of the system to Envisurage, LLC a consultancy run by the former [[CEO]] of the [[Rochester-Genesee Regional Transportation Authority]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Kaffer|first=Nancy|title=Bing: Detroit won't run out of cash in April \u2014 thanks to cuts, more revenue|url=http://www.crainsdetroit.com/article/20120105/FREE/120109964/bing-detroit-wont-run-out-of-cash-in-april-thanks-to-cuts-more-revenue|accessdate=19 February 2012|newspaper=Crain's Detroit Business|date=5 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bukowski|first=Diane|title=Bing to slash bus routes; DDOT routes Feb. 24|url=http://voiceofdetroit.net/2012/02/09/bing-to-slash-bus-routes-d-dot-jobs-feb-24-contractor-gets-big/|accessdate=19 February 2012|newspaper=Voice of Detroit|date=9 February 2012}}</ref> On March 3, 2012, 24-hour service was discontinued, and other weekday and weekend routes and services were pared down, or eliminated entirely, in an attempt to produce savings for the department.<ref>{{cite news|last=Phelps, Greenwood|first=Laura, Tom|title=Changes to Detroit bus service in effect|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/article/20120303/METRO05/203030348/Changes-Detroit-bus-service-effect|accessdate=4 March 2012|newspaper=The Detroit News|date=3 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In August 2013, management of DDOT was contracted out to [[MV Transportation]] under the direction of Paul Toliver until September 2014. Dan Dirks was appointed director of the department by mayor [[Mike Duggan]] on January 9, 2014 for the duration of MV Transportation's contract.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mayor Duggan Names Dan Dirks as DDOT Director|url=http://www.detroitmi.gov/News/tabid/3196/ctl/ReadDefault/mid/4561/ArticleId/386/Default.aspx|accessdate=19 February 2014|newspaper=City of Detroit Department of Communications and Creative Services|date=9 January 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225134039/http://www.detroitmi.gov/News/tabid/3196/ctl/ReadDefault/mid/4561/ArticleId/386/Default.aspx|archivedate=25 February 2014}}</ref> MV Transportation's contract was extended for another two years on August 12, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=City of Detroit Extends Administrative Support Services Contract with MV Transportation|url=http://www.mvtransit.com/node/521|website=www.mvtransit.com/|publisher=MV Transportation|accessdate=11 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111090335/http://www.mvtransit.com/node/521|archive-date=11 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> On January 23, 2016, DDOT reintroduced 24-hour service on three principal routes along with other smaller service changes.<ref>{{cite web|title=DDOT Service Change Proposal, January 2016|url=http://www.detroitmi.gov/Portals/0/docs/deptoftransportation/pdfs/Hearing1601_preview15_1.pdf|website=detroitmi.gov/|accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref> On September 1, 2018, the ten most popular routes, which were renumbered Routes 1-10, received 24/7 service among other changes. Also, old routes 7, 9, and 10 were given higher route numbers to avoid conflict.<ref name=changes/>\n\n===Detroit Downtown Trolley===\n[[File:Detroit Downtown Trolley on Jefferson Avenue, May 1991.jpg|thumb|right|An ex-Lisbon streetcar on Jefferson Avenue in 1991]]\nThe Detroit Downtown Trolley (originally the Detroit Citizen's Railway) was a [[heritage trolley]] built in 1976 as a U.S. Bicentennial project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jtbell.net/transit/Detroit/Trolley/|title=Detroit Downtown Trolley|website=www.jtbell.net|accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref>  The trolley ran over a one-mile L-shaped route from Grand Circus Park to near the Renaissance Center, via Washington Boulevard and Jefferson Avenue, using narrow-gauge trams acquired from municipal rail services outside the U.S.  Most of the Detroit cars that saw service from 1976 to 2003 had been acquired from [[Trams in Lisbon|Lisbon, Portugal]]. Many Detroiters old enough to remember streetcar service from before 1956 were delighted with the nod to nostalgia that the service represented, but lack of business activity in downtown Detroit meant that ridership of the Downtown Trolley never became more than a novelty and declined to only about 3000 per year in the late 1990s; service was suspended in June 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritagetrolley.org/existDetroit1.htm|title=Detroit, MI|website=www.heritagetrolley.org|accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Fares==\n\n===Standard Fares===\nAll routes, plus the [[QLine]]. The [[Detroit People Mover]] will accept passes.\n\nAll fares below are suspended and are free up to further notice, since mid-March 2020 out of respect of the [[2019-20 Coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 outbreak]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Type !! Fare !! 24-Hour Pass\n|-\n|Adult Base Fare\n|$2\n|$5\n|-\n|Student Fare (with DDOT Student ID)\n|rowspan=3|$0.5\n|rowspan=3|$2\n|-\n|Senior/Disabled^\n|-\n|Medicare Cardholder^^\n|-\n|Children under {{convert|44|in|cm}} with adult (limit 3)\n|colspan=2|Free\n|}\n\n===Pass Fees===\nPasses can be purchased at DDOT headquarters, the Rosa Parks Transit Center as well as businesses and stores around the city. DDOT updated and simplified their fare structure eliminating transfer costs and working with the suburban transit system to have some unified fare options. 24-Hour passes can be bought onboard any bus.\n\n^To receive discounted fares, seniors (age 65+) and disabled passengers must present either DDOT Special Fares ID CARD or State ID with Visual impairment designation.\n\n^^Medicare cardholders pay same rates as children 6&ndash;17, seniors at least 65 & disabled.\n\n==Routes==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Route !! Inbound Stops !! Outbound Stops !! Schedule\n|-\n| 1 Vernor ||\n* Michigan/Schaefer\n* Vernor/Salina\n* Vernor/Springwells\n* Vernor/Livernois\n* Vernor/W. Grand Blvd.\n* Bagley/Trumbull\n* Rosa Parks Transit Center\n||\n* Rosa Parks Transit Center\n* Bagley/Trumbull\n* Vernor/W. Grand Blvd.\n* Vernor/Livernois\n* Vernor/Springwells\n* Vernor/Salina\n* Michigan/Schaefer\n||\n* [https://detroitmi.gov/document/1-vernor 1 Vernor Schedule]\n|-\n| 2 Michigan<br /><br /> (Mon\u2013Fri) || \n* Fairlane Town Center\n* Michigan/Greenfield\n* Michigan/Schaefer\n* Michigan/Livernois\n* Michigan/14th\n* Rosa Parks Transit Center\n|| \n* Rosa Parks Transit Center\n* Michigan/14th\n* Michigan/Livernois\n* Michigan/Schaefer\n* Michigan/Greenfield\n* Fairlane Town Center\n|| \n* [https://detroitmi.gov/document/2-michigan-mon-fri 2 Michigan Schedule]\n|-\n| 2 Michigan<br /><br /> (Sat\u2013Sun) || \n* Fairlane Town Center\n* Michigan/Greenfield\n* Michigan/Schaefer\n* Michigan/Livernois\n* Michigan/14th\n* Rosa Parks Transit Center\n|| \n* Rosa Parks Transit Center\n* Michigan/14th\n* Michigan/Livernois\n* Michigan/Schaefer\n* Michigan/Greenfield\n* Fairlane Town Center\n|| \n* [https://detroitmi.gov/document/2-michigan-sat-sun 2 Michigan Schedule]\n|-\n| 3 Grand River<br /><br /> (Mon-Fri) || \n* Grand River/7 Mile\n* Grand River/Evergreen\n* Grand River/Greenfield\n* Grand River/Livernois\n* Grand River/Scotten\n* Grand River/Warren\n* Grand River/Times Square\n* Beaubien/Jefferson\n|| \n* Beaubien/Jefferson\n* Michigan/Cass\n* Grand River/Warren\n* Grand River/Grand Blvd.\n* Grand 